---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import Reveal from "../../components/Reveal.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "design-first")!;
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn Claude`}>
  <main>
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        <strong>Claude Design</strong> (at <code class="inline">claude.ai/design</code>) turns a sentence
        into a working piece of interface. Describe the screen you want; you get a real, interactive prototype
        in seconds — buttons that click, inputs that type, animations that animate.
      </p>

      <h2>What it's for</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Visuals you can show.</strong> Pitches, landing pages, mood boards, prototypes.</li>
        <li><strong>Reusable components.</strong> A pricing table, a loader animation, a hero section — copy-pasted into your real project.</li>
        <li><strong>Design exploration.</strong> Get six versions of an idea in the time it would take to sketch one.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What it's not for</h2>
      <p>It's not a full code generator for your production app — that's where Claude Code shines.
      Design is for the <em>visual</em> layer: how it looks, how it feels, how it behaves on hover.</p>

      <h2>Writing a first prompt</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p style="margin-top: 0;"><strong>A simple template:</strong></p>
        <p style="font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.92rem; background: var(--surface-2); padding: 0.6rem 0.8rem; border-radius: 8px;">
          A [type of screen] for [audience]. [Two or three style words]. Include [content].
        </p>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Worked example:</strong></p>
        <p style="font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 0.92rem; background: var(--surface-2); padding: 0.6rem 0.8rem; border-radius: 8px;">
          A landing page for a sourdough bakery. Warm, hand-drawn, generous whitespace. Hero with a loaf
          photo, a three-card menu section, an order form at the bottom.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2>Style words that work well</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Tone:</strong> playful, serious, premium, retro, brutalist, soft, technical, friendly.</li>
        <li><strong>Density:</strong> generous whitespace, compact, dashboard-dense.</li>
        <li><strong>Inspiration:</strong> "like Linear", "like a Japanese menu", "like an old paperback".</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="tip">
        <strong>Don't over-specify on the first try.</strong> Get a rough version in front of your eyes,
        then iterate. It's much easier to react to a draft than to predict perfection.
      </div>

      <Reveal q="Can I export the code?">
        Yes. Once you're happy, the design panel gives you the HTML/CSS/React you can drop into your project.
      </Reveal>
      <Reveal q="Does it use my real brand colours?">
        Tell it. "Use #1F2937 for headings and #F97316 for accents." Or upload a brand guide and reference it.
      </Reveal>
    </LessonShell>
  </main>
</Layout>
